			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">The cartridge port isn't going to allow you to read or see the 128KB of RAM in real time. What I think tepples suggests is a device that would basically take over cpu control temporarily to dump the contents of RAM. But this would not come even close to matching an emulator with a debugger which can set break points or watch an area of RAM in real time. <br /><br />The real system will always have limits for debugging that the emulators will not. The emulator can stop execution at any time and tell you exactly what the state of everything is. On real hardware it's impossible to fully save the state of everything and you definitely can't freeze everything. <br /><br />Another thing that would help would be to give some examples of what you hope the device you want would allow you to do.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

